"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-w-h-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833372?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">康纳·马克·詹姆森</span></div></div></div><p>这位致力于保护英格兰鸟类的人的神秘而矛盾的生活。<em>克里斯托夫·伊姆舍尔评论</em></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-w-h-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿童读物：<strong>失落、困惑和渴望记住</strong></a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832047?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption">琳达·舒特 (Linda Shute) 绘制的《提醒我》<span class="wsj-article-credit">尼尔·波特 (Neal Porter)</span>插图</div></div></div><p>对《西尔维斯特的信》、《提醒我》、《也许是鲸鱼》、《寻找巨型北极水母》和《放射性蜘蛛来了》的评论。<em>梅根·考克斯·格登的评论</em></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-bereft-bewildered-and-eager-to-remember-73aca8da?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">五佳：论网球界的女性</a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832581?width=700&amp;height=469" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">美联社</span></div></div></div><p>由《宫廷女王：网球传奇爱丽丝·马布尔的众多人生》一书的作者玛德琳·布莱斯 (Madeleine Blais) 评选。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-women-in-tennis-3ecef071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读文章</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Bee Sting’ Review: When Did It All Go Wrong?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在保罗·默里的小说中，一个富裕的家庭的地毯被拔掉了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833512?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-sacks" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨姆·萨克斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 4:03（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>保罗·默里在他的长篇小说《蜂蜇》中讲述了爱尔兰本土红松鼠的悲伤故事。一个多世纪前，白金汉公爵向爱尔兰乡村庄园的一对新婚夫妇送了一个柳条篮，里面装有十几只北美灰松鼠。当礼篮在草坪上被隆重地打开时，松鼠们就冲进了森林。很快，“就像殖民主义的寓言一样”，它们在整个岛上繁殖起来。灰松鼠携带松鼠痘病毒，但对其免疫，这种病毒会使红松鼠的嘴周围出现病变，使它们无法进食。就这样，因为一份结婚礼物，整个物种被推向灭绝的边缘。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/3e98949a-0a13-451e-86b6-aed43c023259.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>巴尼斯家族是默里先生家族传奇中遭受灾难困扰的爱尔兰本土家族。从外表上看，他们是这座无名小城市羡慕的对象。迪基是一家家长，经营着从父亲那里继承的当地汽车经销店，并一直住在他儿时的房子里，后院有一片巨大的林地。他的妻子伊梅尔达是一位著名的美女，她像武术黑带一样挥舞着信用卡。他们的孩子 Cass 和 PJ 在物质条件优越的情况下长大。这是一次完美的国内伊卡洛斯飞行，让坠机坠落到地球上。</p><p>造成这一切的原因是2008年银行业危机后的爱尔兰经济萧条，导致迪基的经销店濒临破产，并迫使伊梅尔达在 eBay 上出售她的名牌服装，这是一种耻辱。财务崩溃对家庭成员来说是一种违约行为——正如 PJ 所说，“缓慢而有条不紊地破坏了他认为真实的一切”——并使他们对以前认为理所当然的行为产生了深深的怀疑。伊梅尔达抱怨某种长期存在的人格缺陷，导致迪基被动地接受自己的毁灭。卡斯承诺进入三一学院的入学资格现在面临风险，她开始想知道她的父母还隐瞒了什么。为什么披风上的家庭照片中没有结婚照？酒吧里那个醉酒的老家伙说伊梅尔达曾经和迪基死去的弟弟弗兰克订婚，这是什么意思？</p><p>随着《蜜蜂蜇伤》继续巴尼斯夫妇的故事，它开始解开过去的事件，通过模糊的因果关系向后移动，就像倒转的多米诺骨牌视频一样。 “当你回顾过去时，你无法判断自己究竟错在哪里，”迪基认为。 “这是一次失误吗？”本书所探讨的问题是为什么事情会这样发生。每个家庭的背景中是否都存在某种原罪，预示着堕落的到来，松鼠被释放、未来被决定的决定性时刻？另一本书可能会通过调查命运或机会来探索这个谜团，但《蜂蜇》是一部爱尔兰小说，充满了迷信和预言（伊梅尔达的阿姨罗丝会读茶叶，并且有“闪现”的千里眼），所以这个问题更好措辞：有诅咒之类的东西吗？ </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>如果说这部小说是爱尔兰小说，那就是另一种更讨人喜欢的概括：从风格上讲，它很出色，其特点是柔和、引人入胜的散文和超自然的讲故事感。即使牢记 20 世纪爱尔兰文学的奇迹，这个小岛上仍在涌现的写作质量仍然令人惊叹。包括默里先生在内的四位爱尔兰作家刚刚入围布克奖长名单，该奖向世界各地的英语小说开放。该国的人才名单包括：安妮·恩莱特 (Anne Enright)、凯文·巴里 (Kevin Barry)、萨拉·波美 (Sara Baume)、唐纳尔·瑞安 (Donal Ryan)、埃米尔·麦克布莱德 (Eimear McBride)、约翰·班维尔 (John Banville)、克莱尔·路易斯·贝内特 (Claire-Louis Bennett)、塞巴斯蒂安·巴里 (Sebastian Barry)、克莱尔·基冈 (Claire Keegan)、科尔姆·托宾 (Colm Tóibín)、艾玛·多诺霍 (Emma Donoghue) 和伯纳德·麦克拉维蒂 (Bernard MacLaverty)，提供了一份不完整的名单——也非常多样化，包括对光荣文学传统的更新以及蓬勃发展的前卫艺术。</p><p>穆雷在这一切中的地位似乎正在发生变化。在《蜂蜇》之前，称他为爱尔兰最好的喜剧小说家是有道理的，因为他的搞笑而恐怖的寄宿学校欢闹剧《Skippy Dies》（2010）以及较小程度上的《标记与虚空》（2015） ），一部尖锐的银行讽刺作品被叙事噱头削弱了一些。但这部新小说虽然常常很有趣，但有着更严肃的意图。默里先生总是能够令人眼花缭乱、令人愉悦，但他以前从未塑造过具有如此深度或悲剧能力的角色。</p><p> 《蜜蜂蜇伤》的细节如此丰富，读起来就像四本书交织在一起一样，因为巴恩斯家族的每个成员都被分配了一个以自由间接引语呈现的冗长部分。卡斯在高中的最后一年，主要专注于保持她受欢迎且控制欲强的好朋友伊莱恩的好感，而默里先生很好地将幻灭、同侪压力和性觉醒等元素融合在一起，这些元素标志着她陷入困境成熟。 PJ 更年轻，也更理智，大部分时间都由他自己决定，他的部分采取了惊悚片的形式：受到恶霸的威胁，他考虑逃到都柏林去和他在网上认识的一个朋友住在一起，而这个朋友，很明显对读者来说，是一个伪装成孩子的掠夺性成年人。</p><p>当小说占据伊梅尔达的脑海时，它完全陷入了过去。默里先生借用了《尤利西斯》中莫莉·布鲁姆的独白来想象这个朴实的人物，他的思想没有标点符号地表达（尽管大写字母仍然表示新句子的开始，因此章节并不难读）。伊梅尔达有着“可以剥掉油漆的口音”，出身于贫困和暴力，是一位残暴的前拳击手的独生女，她与盖尔足球明星、富裕的巴恩斯家族的金童弗兰克的求爱，是她的一生的追求。逃生手段。当弗兰克在一场车祸中去世时——他穿着结婚礼服被埋葬——伊梅尔达又陷入了不确定的境地，直到她抓住了同样茫然和悲伤的迪基提供的救生衣。</p><p>迪基是否表现得很有男子气概，在婚姻和家族事业中接替了他哥哥的位置，或者他的替代是否违反了自然秩序？这些章节从他的角度回顾了他的大学时光，虽然不应该在这里剧透，但它们介绍了更多他看似令人垂涎的家庭生活本应隐藏的秘密。当这些秘密面临曝光的威胁时，一种复杂且高度有益的模糊感开始附着在情节的转折上。一种可怕的不可避免的感觉继续向巴恩斯家族袭来，预示着他们的解散，但也很明显，他们在选择和坚持自己的道路上是同谋，而诚实的变革性行为可能会改变他们的结果。</p><p>通过一系列悬疑的曲折和佯攻，默里先生分别推进了角色的故事，然后集体推进，最后一个精彩的部分将四个人聚集在一起。只有在<em>戏剧的</em>最后<em>一击中</em>，当巧合带来真正的四向碰撞时，戏剧才会给人一种粗暴、被操纵的感觉，而不是有机地展开。</p><p>但到目前为止，我们已经花了很多时间与角色相处，我们对他们生活的投资已经得到了保证。这本有点十九世纪风格的小说的优点在于，它允许在因果链之外推动每个人前进的现实时刻。令人震惊的同情之光撕裂了秘密和自我参与的帷幕。考虑到父亲身份的脆弱性，迪基认为：“你无法保护你所爱的人——这是历史的教训，因此他突然意识到，爱一个人就意味着要承受极大的痛苦。”后来，在一次罕见的对弟弟的关心中，卡斯也有了同样的认识：“这一定就是为人父母的感觉，不断担心你的孩子在你移开视线的那一刻就会被消灭。这一定就是他们如此疯狂的原因。”在坦率与欺骗、无助与绝望的预防的摇摇欲坠的混合中，默里先生描绘了一幅高度但真实的家庭之爱的肖像。</p><p>奇怪的是没有结婚照怎么办？卡斯听到的解释是，当伊梅尔达开车去教堂时，一只蜜蜂被困在她的面纱后面并蜇了她的眼睛下方，留下了一道伤痕，但她的虚荣心不允许记录下来。卡斯带着十几岁的气愤，把这个故事视为她父母有多么可笑的证据，也是他们失败的预兆。真正的原因在《蜂蜇》的过程中逐渐揭示出来，事实证明，它更复杂、更人性化，也更可怕。他们应该选择哪一个：继续在令人安慰的谎言的迷宫中前进，还是接受痛苦的后果——也许还有自由——说出事情的真相？</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。萨克斯是《华尔街日报》的小说评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d<author><![CDATA[Sam Sacks]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Romantic’ Review: Scenes of a Century]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>威廉·博伊德的全景小说讲述了拿破仑的最后一战、斯里兰卡的恐怖以及与拜伦勋爵的谈话。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833545?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">日内瓦迪奥达蒂别墅，威廉·普尔瑟雕刻。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：G. Dagli Orti/Bridgeman Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">布鲁克·艾伦</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 3:54 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a-century-fc855e30"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>从他的第一部小说《非洲好人》开始，威廉·博伊德在四十多年的时间里赢得了声誉，成为可靠、有文化、令人愉快的商业小说的提供者，这些小说通常以有吸引力的历史或地理环境为背景。他的最新作品《浪漫主义》，就像它的几部前作，包括广受欢迎的《任何人心》一样，被博伊德先生称为“一生小说”：对主人公从摇篮到坟墓的描述。必然是他所经历的时代的写照。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/dc3c8cb1-8a29-4235-8fb6-02804ed85976.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 《任何人的心》、《甜蜜的爱抚》和《新的忏悔》都带着主角穿越了 20 世纪，也就是作者的祖国。不过，在《浪漫派》中，博伊德先生回到了 19 世纪。卡舍尔·格雷维尔·罗斯 (Cashel Greville Ross) 出生于 1700 年代末，是一位爱尔兰地主的私生子。在漫长的一生中，他目睹了本世纪一些最戏剧性的场景。他目睹了滑铁卢的行动，目睹了斯里兰卡第三次康提战争期间的大屠杀，与拜伦和雪莱一家一起游历意大利（他甚至帮助拜伦在维亚雷焦的海滩上火化了雪莱的尸体），遇见了——也失去了——他的爱人。拉文纳的生活（拉斐拉·雷佐伯爵夫人饰），在伦敦格鲁布街当作家，在马萨诸塞州康科德附近耕种土地。（博伊德先生令人惊讶地抵制住了让他的英雄与邻近的超验主义者擦肩而过的诱惑），去了非洲在寻找尼罗河的源头时，他遇到了理查德·伯顿，并与约翰·汉宁·斯皮克发生冲突，成为尼加拉瓜驻的里雅斯特领事（别问！），并在威尼斯结束了他的一生，并被埋葬在圣米歇尔岛。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>这一切应该很有趣。但可惜的是，《浪漫派》是一部疲惫不堪、毫无生气的作品，写起来就好像博伊德先生正在尽职尽责地使用他创造的公式，并且之前使用过它以获得更好的效果。部分问题在于罗斯缺乏个性。在《卫报》一篇关于这部一生小说的文章中，博伊德先生声称读者“开始认同中心人物……”。 。 。以一种不同的、更投入的方式，因为他们拥有所有必要的信息，无论是重要的还是无关紧要的。”好吧，我们可能已经获得了有关罗斯生活的大量信息，但事实是他太平淡了，无法认同，而且肯定太平淡了，不足以作为一部长小说的主线。 “他是谁？”罗斯曾一度沉思自己。 “他是什么？构成他现在的‘是’的‘是’是什么？”答案并不是我们太在意，而是罗斯只是一个文学噱头，用来将各种经过仔细研究的历史场景联系在一起。</p><p>像《烟草因素》（约翰·巴特）和《梅森与狄克逊》（托马斯·品钦）这样的小说可能会令人恼火，因为它们的作者痛苦而自觉地努力将历史语言和思潮融入他们的个人风格。博伊德先生甚至没有尝试一下。罗斯和他的许多朋友和同事基本上都说现代英语，偶尔会加入“withal”等句号。“尊敬的先生，”罗斯有一次对他的上级说。 “你从什么时候开始成为康提风俗专家了？”在对话中，像“钱换果酱”（第一次世界大战期间创造的）这样完全不合时宜的表达方式会时不时地出现——这不是作者的笑话，而是显然因为博伊德先生懒得想出这个词。 19世纪的人实际上可能会说的话。那么罗斯所说的这句话呢？ “真可惜。拜伦在比萨。谁能想到呢？真的吗？有时，叙事会从 20 世纪的用语（已经够糟糕了）发展到 21 世纪的用语，比如雪莱圈子被称为“这些特权人士”。正如罗斯所说，天哪！</p><p>博伊德先生选择了 19 世纪最著名的三位演说家——拜伦、雪莱和伯顿——作为他的角色，然后几乎没有给他们任何对话，这一事实表明这本小说是多么三心二意。人们可以理解，对于一个现代作家来说，为传奇天才发明对话一定是令人生畏的，但尝试至少不会有一点乐趣吗？相反，博伊德先生采取了简单的方法，简单地描述了这些著名人物的说话方式。 “伯顿说啊说啊，让每个人都筋疲力尽。 。 。卡舍尔溜走了。他想象伯顿对盐窖和空瓶波特酒喋喋不休，非常高兴有他们作为听众。他显然是一个聪明人，非常聪明——但是却被限制在一个房间里和他在一起。 。 ”。从对伯顿性格的了解来看，人们可以相信这一点。但有精神的小说家不会在挑战面前退缩。</p><p>由于在这个流浪汉故事的每一站，作者总是顽强地把目光投向他的英雄的下一个目的地，有前途的人物和情况突然出现，只是被毫不客气地扔在几页上。罗斯与他的父亲盖伊·斯蒂尔威尔爵士的复杂关系一开始很有趣，但当盖伊爵士去世时，他在儿子的生活中似乎并不比过往游行中的其他人更有意义。罗斯在写作生涯中遇到的几位伦敦文学家——<em>沙龙作家</em>埃塔琳达·达文波特和不诚实的出版商普维斯·耶尔弗顿——都很优秀，但他们很快就被抛在了后面。罗斯与拜伦的情人克莱尔·克莱尔蒙特享受的田园诗般的生活提供了令人兴奋的可能性，但它以失败告终，罗斯继续前进。博伊德先生偶尔会谈到参与 19 世纪生活的真实感受，就像罗斯在阔别多年后回到英国时，对铁路旅行的革命性影响感到震惊一样：“一切都变得‘正常’了。” ’以惊人的速度。”但这些都是转瞬即逝的时刻。</p><p>人们想知道博伊德先生的目标读者是谁？任何对拜伦和雪莱圈子、非洲探索或伦敦文学真正感兴趣的人，都不会在这些页面中发现任何重要内容。任何想要寻找引人入胜的爱情故事的人都不会在罗斯和他的拉斐拉的传统浪漫故事中找到这样的故事。这本小说可以作为新手对这一时期的介绍，有点像 19 世纪的 101。但对于博伊德先生享有盛誉的作家来说，设定的门槛很低。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。艾伦经常为《华尔街日报》撰写书籍和艺术文章。她在本宁顿学院的监狱教育计划中任教。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a- century-fc855e30</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a- century-fc855e30<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>威廉·博伊德</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Finding W.H. Hudson’ Review: The Enigmatic Birdman]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位致力于保护英格兰鸟类的人的神秘而矛盾的生活。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833372?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">弗兰克·布鲁克斯 (Frank Brooks) 创作的 WH 哈德森 (WH Hudson) 肖像细节，悬挂在英国桑迪皇家鸟类保护学会总部的壁炉上方。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：康纳·马克·詹姆森</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">克里斯托夫·伊姆舍尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 3:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-w-h-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>威廉·亨利·哈德森（William Henry Hudson，1841-1922 年）是英国皇家鸟类保护学会的创始成员之一，当他高高地骑在 Sunbeam 自行车上，在英国乡村漫步，寻找他心爱的羽毛鸟时，一定引起了人们的注意。朋友们。他身材瘦小，穿着粗花呢、背心和系带靴子，看上去比英国人还要英国人，帽子里藏着一块湿手帕，让自己保持凉爽。有些人认为，哈德逊目光敏锐，不断移动，就像一只野鸟——也许是一只鹰，或者一只鹰。康纳·马克·詹姆森在他的新传记中报道说，他的笑声听起来像绿色啄木鸟的声音，并补充说，他再也听不到那只鸟的声音而不想起哈德逊。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/5c97296d-3812-49f1-a3ab-57624157eade.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在詹姆森先生在英国皇家鸟类保护协会办公室工作的 25 年里，一幅哈德逊的肖像画，手持双筒望远镜，眯着眼睛，在壁炉架上默默地凝视着他。詹姆森先生是剑桥郡的作家和自然资源保护主义者，他决心恢复哈德森的声音。他梳理了档案，寻找他的英雄的踪迹，并蜿蜒穿越英国——有时自己骑着自行车——重现哈德森的旅行（当他在哈德森也听到过的地方发现一只金翅雀时，他感到非常高兴）。结果是一本活泼、对话式的书，散布着自传旁白，创造性地融合了侦探工作和叙事直觉（“我们只能猜测”），就像它的主题一样难以确定。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>如果最后的“寻找 WH Hudson”并没有真正“找到”WH Hudson，那也是理所当然的。哈德森甚至对他最亲密的朋友来说也是一个谜。首先，他并不是真正的英国人。吉列尔莫·恩里克（Guillermo Enrique）出生于阿根廷，父母来自美国，邻居们都称呼他为吉列尔莫·恩里克（Guillermo Enrique），他在潘帕斯草原上长大，周围有马、羊和牛群，一座小图书馆是他与高雅文化世界的唯一联系。哈德森后来烧毁了他的大部分信件，但这并没有阻止传记作者思考他 1874 年移民到英国的原因。在他的《生活在风声中》（2015 年）中，詹姆森先生的努力背后的模型文学评论家贾森·威尔逊提出了一个显而易见的问题：为什么像哈德森这样自称的自然爱好者会决定离开阿根廷这个拥有“广阔的空地、蓝色的天空和没有污染”的国家，并定居在烟灰覆盖、过度拥挤的地方伦敦？詹姆森先生补充了一个同样难以回答的让他全神贯注的问题：为什么一位南美博物学家几乎从到达的那一刻起，就如此热情地致力于拯救一个不属于他自己的国家的野生鸟类？</p><p>哈德逊的一生充满了矛盾。来到英国后，他投身于自然历史写作，源源不断地对南美和家养鸟类进行最美丽的描述，描绘出“云雀的满溢喜悦；黑帽的野性精神；柳鹪鹩的轻盈、细腻的温柔”（《英国鸟类》，1895）。尽管哈德森仍然坚称自己不是“你们这些该死的作家”，但他却因小说《绿楼》（1904）而闻名于世，小说中一名躲在树林里的委内瑞拉政治难民疯狂地爱上了一个女人。名为 Rima 的像鸟一样的丛林生物（事情的结局并不好）。哈德森的丰富遐想后来被拍成了一部好莱坞电影，由瘦长、整洁的安东尼·帕金斯和精灵般的奥黛丽·赫本搭档，奥黛丽·赫本看起来就像刚从更衣室里出来一样。可以说，这种虚假行为甚至更早开始：哈德森本人从未踏足过委内瑞拉的荒野。</p><p>哈德森并没有让人们轻易喜欢他。甚至在来英国之前，他就大声批评达尔文假设某种南美啄木鸟以地面为食，从未拜访过树木。达尔文调整了有问题的段落，但也对这位无礼的“同事”嗤之以鼻，他可能是一个不相信进化论的人，他如此无端地攻击了他。詹姆逊先生对哈德森的“直率”方法给予高度评价，但没有提到达尔文最终被证明是正确的——参见哈德森后来在《拉普拉塔的鸟类》（1920）中毫无歉意的承认。</p><p>尽管如此，哈德逊还是成功地吸引了一大群信徒，而詹姆森先生有时似乎对他们比对哈德逊本人更感兴趣。他的书中巧妙地描绘了哈德逊在英国皇家鸟类保护学会的女性合作者的肖像，以及像“唐·罗伯托”这样的朋友，苏格兰裔西班牙裔政治家坎宁安·格雷厄姆，他喜欢在海德以高乔式的方式炫耀他的马。公园。我们还了解到很多崇拜他的文人，包括约瑟夫·康拉德、约翰·高尔斯华绥和弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫。 （埃兹拉·庞德对哈德森评价很高，把他写进了他的《诗章》中，称“哈迪……比在场的任何人都高”）。哈德逊的超级粉丝是性格古怪的玛格丽特·布鲁克，她是东印度领土沙捞越王的分居妻子，她和哈德逊一样对热带和鸟类学充满热情：她会坐在蓝色扶手椅、绿色扶手椅上迎接来到她的阿斯科特豪宅的访客。鹦鹉附在她的手腕上。</p><p>到詹姆森先生这本无可挑剔的研究著作结束时，吉列尔莫·恩里克的秘密基本完好无损。例如，我们仍然不知道如何看待他与年长得多的女房东艾米莉·温格雷夫（Emily Wingrave）的无性婚姻，或者他与记者的风流韵事（如果确实如此）。琳达·加德纳（Linda Gardiner）是哈德逊死后出版的《稀有、消失和失落的英国鸟类》（1923 年）的编辑。 WH Hudson 本人似乎也有点失落。</p><p>我们确实知道哈德森对离开祖国的决定感到后悔。 “当我想到那片土地如此丰富的鸟类时，”他在《拉普拉塔的鸟类》中叹息道，“我可能在两条向我敞开的道路中选择了一条错误的道路。” But maybe it was precisely this experience of self-induced personal loss, of an opportunity given and then abandoned, that enabled him to be more attentive to losses of a different, larger kind—the disappearance of so many birds from British woods, fields and shores. Mr. Jameson aptly describes the passage of the 1921 Plumage Bill, banning the use of feathers in human clothes, as one of the highlights of Hudson&#39;s life.</p><p> “Finding WH Hudson” gets us close to its odd protagonist, though never closer than Hudson himself got to many of his birds. Recalling a time in his Argentinian youth when he stalked a little red heron (now the striated heron) into a bed of rushes, Hudson admits he at first couldn&#39;t locate the bird anywhere, only to discover, to his surprise, that it had been right next to him, a perfect imitation of a rush, neck and body frozen into an image of unassailable straightness. As Hudson circled around it, the bird turned, too, its motions corresponding exactly to Hudson&#39;s own even as it remained rigidly in place. The elusive Hudson had found his match in nature: “I could not finish admiring, and thought that never had anything so beautiful fallen in my way before.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Irmscher is the author of “The Poetics of Natural History,” available in a new edition with photographs by Rosamond Purcell.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>自然环境</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> Royal Society for the Protection of Birds</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>自然环境</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Wifedom’ Review: A Portrait of Her Marriage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> George Orwell&#39;s first wife played an undervalued role in his literary career—and saw a side of him that didn&#39;t always match his public image. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138551244768456"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833555?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Eileen Orwell with her son, Richard, 1944.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: UCL Special Collections </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138551244768456"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Donna Rifkind</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 12:28 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The short, urgent life of George Orwell owed much of its success to the devotion of his first wife, Eileen O&#39;Shaughnessy. For decades after her early death in 1945, scholars tended to overlook her importance in Orwell&#39;s story. Then, in 2005, six of her witty, detailed letters to a friend were discovered, providing fresh revelations about her nine-year marriage to one of the most beloved of 20th-century British authors. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a8b6e487-9520-40b7-a77c-357853604070.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The letters surfaced too late to inform the major Orwell biographies that had already appeared, though several more recent books use them to restore Eileen&#39;s significance. One of these, “Eileen: The Making of George Orwell,” by Sylvia Topp, was published in 2020 and is so scrupulously detailed that it makes another conventional biography of Eileen hard to justify. But “Wifedom,” by the Australian writer Anna Funder, is an entirely different enterprise.</p><p> Ms. Funder is a boundary-breaking, risk-taking writer whose previous books synthesized memoir, fact and imagination to impressive effect. “Stasiland: Stories From Behind the Berlin Wall” (2003) chronicled her post-1989 encounters with victims and perpetrators of the surveillance culture that dominated life in the East German dictatorship. “All That I Am” (2011), a historical novel set during the rise of Nazism, blended truth and fiction to dramatize the life of the anti-fascist German playwright Ernst Toller. Both books are nuanced, chilling and sometimes bleakly funny. Their siftings among the ashes of totalitarianism are apt preparation for a re-examination of Orwell&#39;s life and times. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> In 2017, Ms. Funder began rereading Orwell and was captured anew by his mission to make an art of political writing. She fell again for his spiky humor, his rigorous anger, the tolling clarity of his sentences. She worked her way through the biographies published between 1972 and 2003, all written by men, and wondered why they minimized the importance of the women in Orwell&#39;s life, notably his wife Eileen. She came upon a diary entry from early 1949, during Orwell&#39;s last illness, about the “incorrigible dirtiness” of women and their “terrible, devouring sexuality.” How was it possible that this champion of the common man harbored such disgust for the common woman? The biographies offered no suitable explanations. “This is how I moved from the work to the life,” she writes, “and from the man to the wife.”</p><p> When the couple first met in 1935, he was a struggling novelist and journalist in London. Eileen had never heard of him, either by his pen name “George Orwell” or his given name of Eric Blair. Instead of getting a university education, he had spent five years in Burma as a colonial policeman, returning to England with a lifelong hatred for hierarchies of every kind and determination to become a writer. Eileen had been an honors student at Oxford, where her tutors included JRR Tolkien and CS Lewis, and was pursuing a master&#39;s degree in psychology. She chucked her career plans to marry Orwell in 1936 and went off to live with him in a 16th-century cottage in Hertfordshire, an hour or so north of London.</p><p> Orwell&#39;s ambitions became Eileen&#39;s as well: to escape what he called “the money-god” through rural self-sufficiency, keeping goats and chickens and planting a vegetable garden, coping with a primitive oven and an overflowing cesspool. He would write books while she would put her energy and talents into serving as his cook, housekeeper, typist, editor, publishing liaison and all-around facilitator. It was a hopeful time, and they were happy.</p><p> At the end of 1936, Orwell went to Spain to fight with the Republicans in the civil war. Eileen followed a few months later. Here Ms. Funder flips Orwell&#39;s classic 1938 account, “Homage to Catalonia,” to place Eileen instead of Orwell in the story&#39;s central role. In “Homage,” Orwell suggests that Eileen was standing by in a Barcelona hotel to send him little luxuries at the front and type up the observations he was sending her. In fact, she was also working as a high-level secretary in the offices of the Britain-based Independent Labour Party, which was infested with Stalinist spies. Ms. Funder combines the facts with imagined passages about Eileen&#39;s emotional state, along with personal observations from Ms. Funder&#39;s own trip to Barcelona to retrace the action. Such formal risks would be disastrous in the hands of a writer with less tact. But they&#39;re successful here, illuminating Eileen&#39;s bravery as she navigated an atmosphere thick with deceit and danger.</p><p> The Orwells spent most of the remaining seven years of their marriage trying to outrun or ignore serious illness: for him, the worsening tuberculosis that he refused to believe he had; for her, the chronic uterine bleeding that left her weak and anemic. Between spells in hospitals and sanatoriums, they carried on, always just scraping by, exhausting themselves with overwork. In addition to books, Orwell wrote mountains of reviews and took editorial jobs for magazines and at the BBC. When war broke out in 1939, Eileen worked as a secretary first at the Ministry of Information and later at the Ministry of Food. She continued to type, edit and contribute to the planning of Orwell&#39;s books; together in bed, they giggled over a little barnyard satire he was concocting. They refused to leave London during the Blitz, dodging bombs and moving house when their ramshackle flats were destroyed.</p><p> Illness and war stepped up Orwell&#39;s impulsiveness. He had never been faithful to Eileen, but now he pursued other women with a near-desperate fervor. Most scholars maintain, with insufficient evidence, that Eileen also had affairs; Ms. Funder has her doubts. Either way, although she was unhappy about Orwell&#39;s infidelities, Eileen never considered leaving him. At his insistence in 1944 they adopted a baby boy, Richard, and hoped eventually to adopt a girl. When Eileen died suddenly on the operating table in March 1945 at age 39, Orwell was absent. He had gone to Europe on assignment as a war correspondent and was enduring another health crisis in a military hospital in Germany when he got the news. Stubbornly reticent, he told a friend that he needed to leave because he had “things to do at home” and would return in a fortnight, which he did.</p><p> In the five years left to him, Orwell at last saw his financial anxieties ease when his barnyard satire, “Animal Farm,” was a surprise hit. Success had come too late for Eileen and was nearly too late for Orwell, who wrote “Nineteen Eighty-Four” between bouts of fever, typing the final draft when he was near total collapse. In a London hospital three months before his death he married a much younger woman, Sonia Brownell, making it clear that he needed a literary executor more than a wife. He was 47 when he died in 1950.</p><p> Ms. Funder clearly believes that Eileen&#39;s role in Orwell&#39;s life has been undervalued, her brilliance and valor underestimated. She balks at the ways Orwell views “women—as wives—in terms of what they do for him, or &#39;demand&#39; of him.” His exalted status, she implies, has obscured how tyrannical this hater of tyrannies could be, how insensitive he was toward the woman who best understood him.</p><p> Ms. Funder insists that she still loves Orwell and doesn&#39;t want to use Eileen as a cudgel to beat him with; yet often she can&#39;t seem to resist. “Wifedom” is most effective when she struggles away from judgment and stretches toward sympathy, as she does in her final pages. Whether sanctifying or demonizing, judgment is a limited tool if the goal is truly to see a committed partnership in all its ambiguity and incoherence, because judgment is always at least as much about the judge. At her best, Ms. Funder shows that radical compassion—which is not the same as forgiveness—will move one closer to understanding, in marriage and biography, every time.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. Rifkind is the author of “The Sun and Her Stars: Salka Viertel and Hitler&#39;s Exiles in the Golden Age of Hollywood.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wifedom-review-orwell-a-portrait-of-her-marriage-fb31ab2c<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>结婚/离婚</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>marriage</category><category> divorce</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘From One Cell’ Review: Blueprints for Building]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Just how do the instructions mapped in the genes create the dizzyingly complex, three-dimensional structures of multicellular life? <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590137130768513918"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834080?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An electron micrograph image of a soil-dwelling hermaphrodite nematode worm.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Science Photo Library/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590137130768513918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Adrian Woolfson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 12:25 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/from-one-cell-review-biology-science-blueprints-for-building-b4c74d17"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In the 1960s, the polymathic Cambridge scientist Sydney Brenner contributed to the deciphering of the genetic code—the mechanism specifying how the DNA sequences of genes are translated into the amino-acid sequences of proteins. In the 1970s, Brenner set out to define another code: the generative biological rules that determine how the genes within a single cell delineate the three-dimensional organization of multicellular organisms. “How genes might specify the complex structures found in higher organisms,” he wrote in a paper on the genetics of the tiny transparent worm <em>C. elegans</em> , “is a major unsolved problem of biology.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/501572ce-3571-4c93-8508-326c92c08a38.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Once cracked, this generative code of living things could convey humankind with an unimaginable ability to modify the structures of living things. It also has the potential to help us address such enigmas as why we get ill and the mechanism behind aging. Brenner&#39;s brilliance was to realize that a problem of this importance and complexity would only be tractable if studied in simple model organisms. The otherwise inconsequential <em>C. elegans</em> was perfectly suited to this task. It comprised only 959 cells and had a conveniently short three-day reproductive cycle.</p><p> Decades later, despite considerable progress in the field of evolutionary development, or evo-devo, the generative rules of biology have not yet been adequately defined. In his insightful and erudite “From One Cell,” the University of Pennsylvania doctor and researcher Ben Stanger details the “foundational discoveries” that have contributed to our current understanding. All were made in model systems of differing complexities, ranging from viruses and bacteria to sea anemones, flies, frogs and mice.</p><p> The relevance of such organisms to the biology of human beings was summarized by the French scientist Jacques Monod, who stated that “What is true for E. coli is true for the elephant.” This maxim referenced the universality of biological structures and the biochemical unity of all life on Earth, resulting from its shared evolutionary origin. A similar sentiment was expressed by the 19th-century French embryologist Étienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, who stated that there is, “philosophically speaking, only a single animal.” Nature, in her parsimony, appears to have used a similar method for building all animals, and indeed all living things.</p><p> The key conundrum in the development of a human being from a zygote—the single-celled product of the fusion of an egg and sperm—is how a uniform set of genetic instructions is differentially programmed to produce multiple cell types that self-organize into a distinct three-dimensional form. We now know that the secret to building organisms resides in gene regulation. Different cell types activate and repress genes in distinct ways, just as in an orchestra a cellist and an oboist might look at the same score but follow only their designated parts. The unique regulatory fingerprint superimposed onto a cell&#39;s genome is known as its epigenome, which is established through chemical modifications to regulatory regions of genes and the histone proteins they associate with. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> Dr. Stanger artfully guides us through key experiments that contributed to the foundations of our knowledge about embryonic development, and he provides sketches along the way of some of the researchers involved. The author also highlights the role played by serendipity and Nature&#39;s coquettish revelation of unexpected phenomena. When the bow-tie-wearing “child of privilege” Ernest McCulloch found himself thrown together with James Till who was “raised on a farm in rural Saskatchewan,” it was Till&#39;s pragmatism coupled with McCulloch&#39;s impetuosity that led to the discovery of the first multipotent stem cell, capable of generating a full set of human blood cells.</p><p> Another illuminating passage is the author&#39;s account of John Gurdon, the quintessential English gentleman, Nobel laureate and discoverer of nuclear cloning. Mr. Gurdon&#39;s achievements stemmed from his frustrated attempts at studying entomology, and he only developed the manual dexterity necessary to manipulate cell nuclei through his hobby, the construction of miniature scale models of trains, boats and planes. That Mr. Gurdon came last in a biology class of 250 students in high school illustrates a recurrent theme in science. Many high achievers have atypical intellectual abilities not captured by conventional “intelligence” metrics.</p><p> The book contains several intriguing revelations. One is that “tumors do not invent new biology, but instead use existing biology in new ways.” They inappropriately activate genes invoked in embryogenesis. Development and cancer are intertwined, the author explains, with each cancer being in effect “its own species.” Another surprise is the ease with which substantive biological modifications can be achieved. The Japanese Nobel laureate Shinya Yamanaka showed, in a trick worthy of the escapologist Harry Houdini, that differentiated cells could be coaxed to “travel back in time” and revert to an undifferentiated pluripotent state capable of generating all cell types.</p><p> Dr. Stanger briefly touches on the therapeutic potential of Dr. Yamanaka&#39;s induced pluripotent stem cells and the recent misuse of genome editing. But he does not address the most powerful genome-modification method of all. The emerging new science of synthetic genomics coupled with artificial intelligence should enable genomes to be authored and synthesized from scratch. This will play a pivotal role in defining the generative laws of biology. Once such rules have been defined, they will have the potential to significantly influence the future of our species.</p><p> The author largely avoids any discussion of the potential risks and utilities of such discoveries, stating that he does not wish to conjure up “some fantastical image of a utopian or dystopian future.” But we do need to discuss the future, one way or another. To state that “the benefits must be weighed against the risks” is inadequate in an environment where, as the author puts it, “gaps continue to widen between scientists and the public” as well as between “scientists and other scientists.”</p><p> Avoiding any substantive discussion of potential consequences is unfortunately common in contemporary popular accounts of molecular genetics. It would be more responsible for authors and experts to forthrightly address them.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Woolfson is the author of “An Intelligent Person&#39;s Guide to Genetics.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/from-one-cell-review-biology-science-blueprints-for-building-b4c74d17</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/from-one-cell-review-biology-science-blueprints-for-building-b4c74d17<category>生物学</category><category>Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Gene/Cell Therapy</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category>健康</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>生物学</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>gene</category><category> cell therapy</category><category> arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>medical treatments</category><category> procedures</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Daughter of the Dragon’ Review: The Star From Chinatown]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Anna May Wong&#39;s captivating presence made her a global celebrity during film&#39;s silent era. But Hollywood prejudices kept lead roles away. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138540417552162"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833247?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Anna May Wong in the 1934 film &#39;Java Head.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Everett Collection </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138540417552162"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Julia Flynn Siler</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 12:24 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/daughter-of-the-dragon-review-the-movie-star-from-chinatown-90311c2f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The 1922 silent film “The Toll of the Sea,” a variation on “Madame Butterfly” set in Hong Kong, introduced audiences to the first hit <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCLRY" class="company-name">Technicolor</a> movie—and to an alluring performer in its lead role. Anna May Wong burst into the Hollywood firmament as the world&#39;s first Chinese American cinema star. She would eventually appear in more than 60 films, a dozen stage plays, several television series and countless vaudeville shows. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a1752445-7dbf-4e07-8b48-d2da70c2a97e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> From silents in the 1920s to movies with sound in the 1930s and 1940s and television in the 1950s, Wong landed many roles, often as a conniving servant or scheming “Dragon Lady.” But even before the American movie industry adopted the repressive Production Code of 1930, Wong could not be seen kissing a white man on-screen for fear of violating prohibitions on interracial relationships. As Yunte Huang writes in his sympathetic biography, “Daughter of the Dragon: Anna May Wong&#39;s Rendezvous With History,” she grappled with this “racial attitude that imposed a virtual form of foot-binding on Wong throughout her career.”</p><p> Mr. Huang is the author of two highly-regarded biographies of Chinese American cultural icons—2009&#39;s “Charlie Chan,” which contrasted the fictional “Honorable Detective” with his real-life Honolulu counterpart, and 2018&#39;s “Inseparable,” the story of the famous conjoined twins Chang and Eng Bunker. “Daughter of the Dragon” is a strong complement to those earlier works, particularly in its exploration of “Hollywood&#39;s enduring tradition of yellowface”—the practice of casting white actors playing Asian characters. Mr. Huang proves an incisive guide to the tangle of race, politics, and business that Anna May Wong encountered during her rise to fame. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> Born in 1905 into the “steam and starch of her father&#39;s laundry” in Los Angeles&#39;s Chinatown, Wong began her career at age 14, recruited as one of hundreds of extras from her neighborhood for the 1919 silent film “The Red Lantern.” On set, she met the film&#39;s female star, Alla Nazimova, who drew the willowy teen into her “sewing circle,” a discreet gathering of lesbian and bisexual thespians. Not long after, Wong began an affair with a married male director, who soon dropped her. Her concerned mother told her “I wish you would not have so many pictures taken. Eventually you may lose your soul.” Ambitious and beautiful, Wong ignored her mother&#39;s advice, quitting high school in pursuit of stardom.</p><p> At 17 she landed her first leading role in “The Toll of the Sea,” earning critical praise for her emotive performance as Lotus Flower, a young Chinese woman whose affair with a white man turns tragic. The film&#39;s success led to a supporting role in 1924&#39;s “The Thief of Bagdad,” starring Douglas Fairbanks, the biggest male star of the time.</p><p> Wong was cast in that film as a scantily clad, duplicitous slave—not a love interest. It would become a pattern throughout her career: American studio bosses put her in supporting roles rather than romantic leads because of her race. “Shanghai Express,” a 1932 film about war-torn China directed by Josef von Sternberg, became a star vehicle not for Wong, but for the director&#39;s new discovery, Marlene Dietrich. In what is widely considered to be Wong&#39;s best performance, she played with nuance the character of Hui Fei, a reformed prostitute, who defeats a villain to settle a personal score.</p><p> After filming “Shanghai Express” and not being offered a movie contract by its Depression-rattled studio Paramount, Wong followed the example of Josephine Baker and other American performers of color to leave America for better opportunities in Europe. Demonstrating a flair for fashion, she soon became an international style icon, memorably telling a German reporter “You can forgive a woman for a face that is not beautiful more easily than for a dress that isn&#39;t.”</p><p> In “Java Head,” one of the three films she made in England in 1934, Wong finally received her very first film kiss from a white man—a light peck on the chin between married characters, with the camera angle blocking the view of the lips. As Mr. Huang writes, the “&#39;kissing taboo&#39; might have been broken, but the curse remained.” Wong, who that same year had been dubbed “The World&#39;s Best Dressed Woman,” “was still a beauty no one was allowed to kiss.”</p><p> Her private life was also marked by loneliness. At 19, she told the South China Morning Post, “I am tall, and I have large eyes . 。 。 I am independent, and Chinese men don&#39;t like that.” Meanwhile, laws against miscegenation (which held force in many states until the Supreme Court struck them down in 1967) barred her from marrying outside of her race. Wong never had a long-term relationship and had no children of her own.</p><p> Wong visited China for the first time in 1936, writing about her trip in serialized form for the New York Herald Tribune. Her first-person observations are delightful—in a Nanking Road silk shop, she wrote, “it seemed as if the aurora borealis had been broken into bits and distributed through the shop.” By contrast, Mr. Huang&#39;s own descriptions can grow overwrought. His take on the nightlife Wong found in Shanghai casts it as “a mad dance with eschatological overtures on the edge of an erupting volcano—an endless party before the end of the world as they knew it.”</p><p> Although Wong&#39;s trip to China was personally meaningful, it didn&#39;t quell her critics or help her land important roles. Three years later, in the 1937 film version of “The Good Earth,” Wong lost out on the lead to Luise Rainer. With its cast largely made up of white actors, the film based on Pearl Buck&#39;s bestselling book became, as Mr. Huang calls it, a “yellowface extravaganza.” An influential Chinese official had let it be known to studio heads that, given her “tainted reputation,” giving Wong the leading role would be detrimental to the film&#39;s fate in China.</p><p> During World War II, Wong took parts in films like “Bombs Over Burma,” and focused on sending relief money to war-torn China. In the decade that followed, her career sputtered and she started drinking heavily. In 1953 she contracted cirrhosis of the liver, prompting a hospital stay and recovery in a sanitarium. A number of roles in television revived her working life, and, by the early 1960s, she appeared on the cusp of a major comeback as one of the lead roles in a planned film version of the hit Broadway musical, “Flower Drum Song.” Sadly, before filming could begin, Wong died in 1961 at her home in Santa Monica. She was 56 years old.</p><p> Because Mr. Huang relies heavily on secondary sources, the star&#39;s inner life remains frustratingly opaque. But “Daughter of the Dragon” offers a lively tour through Wong&#39;s world and filmography, and the film stills and portraits included throughout are a particular pleasure. Mr. Huang turns the spotlight back onto an important but largely forgotten film icon—one who shone brightly despite the bitter racial bias she faced throughout her long career.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. Siler is a former WSJ staff reporter and the author of “The White Devil&#39;s Daughters: The Women Who Fought Slavery in San Francisco&#39;s Chinatown.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/daughter-of-the-dragon-review-the-movie-star-from-chinatown-90311c2f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/daughter-of-the-dragon-review-the-movie-star-from-chinatown-90311c2f<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Merrick Garland Names David Weiss as Special Counsel in Hunter Biden Investigation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>司法部长表示，韦斯作为特拉华州的美国检察官处理调查，他请求任命<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834098?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">司法部长梅里克·加兰试图与亨特·拜登的调查保持距离。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chip Somodevilla/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日中午 12:22 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——周五，司法部长梅里克·加兰任命特拉华州联邦检察官大卫·韦斯为特别检察官，继续对亨特·拜登进行调查，在他的父亲、总统拜登<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-and-hunter-biden-ignores-political-perils-and-embraces-scandal-plagued-son-f105aee2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">竞选总统</a>之际，这为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-limbo-republicans-749b5187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这场长期上演的法律剧</a>开启了充满政治色彩的新篇章。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-and-hunter-biden-ignores-political-perils-and-embraces-scandal-plagued-son-f105aee2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">-选举</a>。</p><p>加兰在一份简短的声明中表示，韦斯周二告诉他，他的调查“已经达到了他应该继续担任特别检察官的工作的阶段，他要求被任命为特别检察官”。</p><p>写信给 Sadie Gurman <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(sadie.gurman@wsj.com)</a>和 Aruna Viswanatha ( <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亨特·拜登</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Country of the Blind’ Review: Journey Into Darkness]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> For many blind people, the loss of eyesight is neither immediate nor total. Blindness is both a physical condition and a state of mind. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590137141057854382"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833374?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590137141057854382"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Claire Shang</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 12:22 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-country-of-the-blind-review-journey-into-darkness-86d1734f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In HG Wells&#39;s 1904 short story “The Country of the Blind,” an explorer tumbles into a remote mountain valley that has been home to 15 generations of blind residents.他们如此彻底和满足地适应了失明，以至于他们无法想象视力意味着什么。安德鲁·利兰（Andrew Leland）借用了这个故事的标题来写他关于患有退行性眼病的引人入胜的回忆录。 “与威尔斯饰演的角色不同，他最终逃脱了，”他写道，“我会留下来，慢慢成为一名入籍公民。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/1b61d1b7-b505-4850-a244-e5cab8734808.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Mr. Leland, now 42, was diagnosed with retinitis pigmentosa as a college freshman. An inherited eye disease with no cure, RP often emerges in youth as night blindness; increasingly limited peripheral vision means that most people with RP are legally blind by middle age. But the condition is notable for its gradualness: There&#39;s no decisive moment of “going blind,” just the ongoing process of “becoming blind.” Mr. Leland retains just 6% of his visual field, and doesn&#39;t know how much longer his residual central vision will stick around.</p><p> As Mr. Leland points out, blindness is often an in-between condition. Only 15% of blind people have no light perception at all. For most blind people, who can see to varying extents, thinking of oneself as blind is prompted as much by mental shifts as by physical changes—at some point, Mr. Leland had to decide that he was blind. He now believes blindness is neither “biological fact” or “social construct” but “somewhere in between these two extremes.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="713" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833381?width=639&amp;height=713" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Andrew Leland</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Gregory Halpern</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Across 10 chapters in “The Country of the Blind,” the author, a writer and podcast producer, weaves his personal experience into a cultural history of blindness that touches on topics including masculinity, race, religion, art and the disability rights movement. He tells the reader that, to research this book, he wanted to go wherever “blindness intersects with contemporary life.” Still, the most memorable parts of his account are intimate moments of pure autobiography.</p><p> When he uses his cane in public for the first time, for instance, it&#39;s on a night of bar-hopping, with the dual protection of darkness and drunkenness. He describes holding it “like a giant fountain pen, doodling on the pavement.” Readers are privy to a host of other life events: passing the tests that qualify him for legal blindness; shakily cutting his son&#39;s umbilical cord, worried that he&#39;ll miss his target; learning which genetic mutation is responsible for his RP. He retires from driving in his early 30s, and from reading printed books a few years later. This new life sometimes feels like “one long troubleshooting session,” he writes. After studying braille for two laborious years, he tries to read a braille picture book to his enthusiastic first-grader. They don&#39;t make it through the book before bedtime.</p><p> In this case as in others, Mr. Leland offers his own experience as a bridge between the blind and sighted worlds. He notes that “talking books,” designed to increase blind people&#39;s access to literature, have existed since the mid-1930s. And it was blind technologists in the early &#39;90s who first developed EPUB, now a widely used ebook format. It&#39;s not clear, though, whether a world of virtual affordances for the blind will immediately improve their lives.</p><p> With the advent of screen reading, the author notes, fewer blind people are learning braille. Many “braille evangelists”—including some of blind professionals—warn of today&#39;s students becoming, “in a technical sense, illiterate.” Underneath the surface of this debate lies an uncomfortable truth about educational disparities: More than a fifth of Americans with a visual disability don&#39;t finish high school, double the rate of sighted Americans, and Mr. Leland recognizes that, with a blind unemployment rate of 70%, “holding a full-time job, any job, is a minority position among the blind.” He wonders how the logistics of his day-to-day as a journalist will change as his vision erodes.</p><p> Blindness, Mr. Leland writes, is at once “central and incidental in a person&#39;s life.” He can still navigate independently by foot—he just has to take into consideration factors he never did previously. He is the same person he was before losing his sight, and he is not. Somewhat less informatively, he argues that “we all live with this sort of ambiguity” in various aspects of life; he suggests his blindness, which doesn&#39;t entail the complete loss of his sight, can be compared to a divorce that doesn&#39;t completely sever a connection between exes. Elsewhere, he likens becoming disabled to unwillingly joining a club. Next, the same zoom-out: “But it&#39;s also a basic feature of contemporary life: you may not like your family, but that&#39;s another club you can&#39;t leave.” The book is best when it doesn&#39;t feel obliged to universalize, but stays with Mr. Leland&#39;s particular journey into blindness.</p><p> By the end of “The Country of the Blind,” Mr. Leland has overcome the earlier shame that delayed his adoption of a cane. But as the cane becomes part of his daily life, he also becomes more aware of how people react to the ubiquitous signal of blindness: pedestrians cross to the other side of the street, parents “yank their children aside when I&#39;m still half a block away.” For Mr. Leland, each stranger becomes a potential adversary, capable of condemning him to social isolation. “This is no way to move through the world,” he realizes. He now pairs his cane with a “half smile,” which—to those strangers inevitably watching—lends him an air of approachability. More important, taking control of how he is seen as he moves through the world reminds him to have patience, with others and himself: “I&#39;m restored to the status of one person encountering another, &#39;with equanimity and friendliness.&#39; ” To borrow a refrain from the book, he has learned to fail with grace—a lesson that, by virtue of its specificity, can&#39;t help but take on broader resonance.</p><p> <em>Ms. Shang is a Robert L. Bartley Fellow at the Journal.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-country-of-the-blind-review-journey-into-darkness-86d1734f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-country-of-the-blind-review-journey-into-darkness-86d1734f<category> Eye Conditions</category><category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>健康</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> eye conditions</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>medical conditions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mysteries: ‘My Men’ by Victoria Kielland]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Plus &#39;The Murder of Anton Livius&#39; by Hansjörg Schneider and &#39;The Mill House Murders&#39; by Yukito Ayatsuji. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138821871284704"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="495" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832432?width=860&amp;height=495" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590138821871284704"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-nolan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tom Nolan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 11, 2023 12:02 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-my-men-by-victoria-kielland-3128a6c1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The Norwegian author Victoria Kielland&#39;s novel “My Men,” translated into English by Damion Searls, is based on the exploits of Belle Gunness, a real-life serial killer (“Hell&#39;s Belle”) who preyed upon Norwegian-speaking wife-seekers in Illinois and Indiana near the turn of the 20th century. She may or may not have died in a 1908 fire at her farm where the bodies or body parts of 30 men, four children and a headless woman were found. History&#39;s Belle was a grim opportunist; Ms. Kielland&#39;s fictional Bella is a more complicated figure: vexed by problematic theology and suffering the legacy of brutal abuse. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/775e36ce-522d-44c6-83b5-3fb181b4460e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “My Men” is a stylistic tour de force, a third-person account of Bella Gunness&#39;s grotesque odyssey as perceived through her own sensorium. It reads like an expressionist prose-poem penned by a stark-minded zealot: “The darkness was exactly the same as the light, just as sinful, just as pure.” Seduced and abandoned by a rich man&#39;s son, the teenage Bella flees Norway to Chicago, where her married sister takes her in. As with her recent “romance,” what first seems sweet to Bella turns sour. Her sister says, “I think you have a nervous condition.” Bella thinks: “All stories end with death.”</p><p> Bella strikes out on her own: marries (officially or not), has children, becomes a widow—more than once. In La Porte, Ind., Belle explains to police how her husband Peder came to bleed to death on the kitchen floor: “He was sitting . 。 。 next to the stove and he bent down to pick up one of his shoes, and he bumped into the stove and the meat grinder . 。 。 fell on his head.” To herself, she&#39;s more candid: “How accurate could memory really be? 。 。 。 She no longer knew what made up the greatest part of her life, the memories or the lies.”</p><p> Ms. Kielland is clearly a gifted writer, and “My Men” is an impressively realized creation. Here&#39;s hoping it acquires the significant readership it deserves. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/01e3c393-7524-4622-a023-472a2304599b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Peter Hunkeler, inspector with the Basel city criminal investigation department, makes his third US appearance in the Swiss writer Hansjörg Schneider&#39;s “The Murder of Anton Livius,” translated by Astrid Freuler. The divorced father of an adult daughter, Peter keeps company with the good-natured and dry-witted Hedwig. The two are woken from their New Year&#39;s Day sleep by a call summoning Hunkeler to work. An elderly Swiss occupant of an allotment on the Alsatian border has been murdered: shot in the forehead, then displayed at his cabin&#39;s front door with a meat hook through his chin, “hanging there like a lump of meat.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> George Orwell&#39;s marriage, the unlikely life of an early Hollywood star, the man who changed American folk music and more.</p></div></div><p> The case provokes jurisdictional chaos. Though the victim lived in Basel, France has control of the crime scene. “We&#39;re not allowed in,” explains Hunkeler&#39;s colleague, “and the French aren&#39;t allowed into Basel. How&#39;s that going to work?” Joint meetings between police and prosecutorial squads deteriorate into insult-filled squabbles. The victim&#39;s history proves no less problematic: Born in East Prussia as Anton Livius, he was accepted into Switzerland in 1945 as a fleeing German soldier and granted citizenship under the name Anton Flückiger. He worked in a warehouse, never married, and had several girlfriends; his German army records can&#39;t be found.</p><p> Is Anton&#39;s death connected to events in his past? Or is it linked to recent doings, such as the slaughter of animals kept by allotment owners? When facts are hard to come by, Hunkeler trades theories informally with a compatible French official he&#39;s met. He then chooses to sidle into the investigation through chats with local strangers over drinks and meals. His ways are quaint: When in the rural wilds, he turns off his phone to get in touch with nature&#39;s rhythms. “You&#39;re a funny one,” a woman who knew Flückiger tells him. “They should put you in a museum.” When he quizzes the mayor of a neighboring town about Fluckiger&#39;s possible ties to the SS, the mayor abruptly cuts him off: “You know, we Alsatians believe the dead should be left to rest.”</p><p> “But that didn&#39;t work,” Hunkeler knows. “It never worked.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/e80644d4-0461-432e-b180-38f9db22e051.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Japanese author Yukito Ayatsuji&#39;s “The Mill House Murders,” translated into English by Ho-Ling Wong, takes place in 1985-86 in a mansion in a valley in a mountainous region where few visitors venture. Three huge mill wheels churn fresh water day and night—almost, says one rare guest, “like they are turning against the flow of time, keeping the house and everything in this valley frozen in a never-ending moment.”</p><p> Built by an architect known for including secret passages and hidden rooms, the mansion is home to Fujinuma Kiichi, the facially disfigured son of a painter whose surrealistic canvases have acquired a cult following. Kiichi, who wears a rubber mask to hide his damaged features, is sole custodian of his father&#39;s oeuvre and refuses to show the works except on the anniversary of the artist&#39;s death, when a few chosen devotees are invited to a private viewing.</p><p> At the 1985 gathering, disaster strikes: During a raging storm, the mansion&#39;s housekeeper falls to her death from the roof tower; a guest is murdered, and another disappears, having apparently stolen one of the late maestro&#39;s works. Come 1986, the dauntless Kiichi is determined to carry on the annual tradition. Guests gather, as do storm clouds: “A large shadow fell upon the house and its surroundings.” A visitor stumbles upon a note: “Leave. Leave this house.” Will mystery repeat itself?</p><p> “The Mill House Murders” is a psychological-mystical thriller built on tropes from cozier crime fiction. Agatha Christie-type stopwatch sequences and John Dickson Carr-style locked-room conundrums coexist with Poe-like Gothic sequences full of severed limbs and charred flesh. There&#39;s a last-minute visitor who says he&#39;s not a policeman but acts like one. And then there&#39;s the late artist&#39;s final work, a disturbing landscape of which Kiichi says: “I&#39;m just as afraid of that painting as my father was.” A two-track narrative alternates “past” (1985) and “present” (1986) chapters, illuminating readers even as it thrusts them into the unfolding dark. Whether this all leads to a rewarding denouement may depend on the reader&#39;s taste, but no one can accuse Mr. Ayatsuji of not sustaining the eerie mood of his strange story until its very last sentence.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 16:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-my-men-by-victoria-kielland-3128a6c1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-my-men-by-victoria-kielland-3128a6c1<author><![CDATA[Tom Nolan]]></author><category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Rampage/Serial Killings</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>rampage</category><category> serial killings</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>